<h2 id="structureforeachgridblock">Structure for each grid block</h2>

<p>Each grid block will begin with either a <code>&lt;section&gt;</code> element and it would not be given any class name. This <code>&lt;section&gt;</code> element will contain a <code>.wrap</code> element which then contains the grid structures. </p>

<p>Here&#8217;s an example</p>
<pre><code class="html">&lt;body&gt;
  &lt;!-- ... --&gt;
  &lt;section&gt;
    &lt;div class=&quot;wrap&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;l-2up--8-4&quot;&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;l-gi&quot;&gt; &lt;/div&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;l-gi&quot;&gt; &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  &lt;/section&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;</code></pre>

<h1 id="howtocodestructureblocksandgridblocks">How to code Structure Blocks and Grid Blocks</h1>

<h2 id="structureblocks">Structure Blocks</h2>

<p>All structure blocks have the following format: </p>

<ol>
<li>A <code>.l-</code> class that signifies that this is a structure block</li>
<li>Several <code>.l-gi</code> classes that are supposed to contain grid blocks.</li>
</ol>
<pre><code class="html">&lt;div class=&quot;l-structure-block-name&quot;&gt;
  &lt;div class=&quot;l-gi&quot;&gt;
    &lt;!-- [[&gt; grid-block-name ]]--&gt;
  &lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

<p>Some structure blocks deviate a little from this format, and will be covered in the Grid structure block page.</p>